===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|screw|lang=enm}}, {{term|scrue|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|frm}} {{term|escroue|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|escroe||nut, socket, screw|lang=fro}}, of uncertain origin.

Perhaps from {{etyl|la}} {{term|scrofa|scrōfa|sow|lang=la}}, referring to the screw-like tip of a boar's penis; yet this development is not found in other Romance languages.

Alternative etymology derives {{etyl|fro|-}} {{term|escroe|lang=fro}} from a {{etyl|gem}} source, from Old {{etyl|frk}} *{{term||scrūva|screw|lang=frk}}, from {{proto|Germanic|skrūbō|screw|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Germanic|skru-|to cut|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|(s)keru-||(s)ker-|to cut|lang=en}}, related to {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Schraube||screw|lang=de}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|schruve|lang=nds}}, {{term|schruwe||screw|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|schroef||screw|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|skrue||screw|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|skruf||screw, peg|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|skrúfa||screw|lang=is}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[simple machine]], a [[helical]] inclined plane.
# A (usually) metal fastener consisting of a [[shank]] partially or completely [[threaded]] [[shank]], sometimes with a threaded point, and a [[head]] used to both hold the top material and to drive the screw either directly into a soft material or into a prepared hole.
# {{nautical}} A ship's [[propeller]].
